sec.p:
The vertical profile of the global trajectory describes how the different flight phases are flown, according to the flight intent. In this article, the flight intents considered are defined by the following general flight segments (based on standard airline operational practice):


take-off run;

initial climb at constant path angle and take-off engine rating (TO);

CAS/Mach climb at maximum climb engine rating (MCLB);

horizontal accelerations at maximum climb engine rating;

cruise at constant pressure altitude (hp) and constant Mach;

cruise step climb at constant Mach and maximum climb engine rating;

Mach/CAS descent at idle engine rating (IDLE);

horizontal decelerations at idle engine rating;

glide path at constant ground path angle and constant CAS;

landing run.

The scalar equations of motion are formulated based on the following general assumptions:


spherical, non-rotating Earth;

rigid and symmetric aircraft;

symmetric flight;

thrust parallel to the aircraft aerodynamic velocity.
These assumptions are appropriate for subsonic, transport aircraft. Hence, the scalar equations of motion are9,10
(1)mdVdt=T-D(V,h,L)-mgsinγ-mVdwdhsinγcosγmVdγdt=L-mgcosγ+mVdwdhsin2γdmdt=-m·F(V,h,T)(RE+h)dϕdt=(Vcosγ+w)cosχA(RE+h)cosϕdλdt=(Vcosγ+w)sinχAdhdt=Vsinγ
where V, γ, and χA are the aerodynamic velocity modulus, path angle, and heading angle, φ, λ, and h the geodetic coordinates of the aircraft centre of mass (latitude, longitude, and altitude), t the time, T the thrust, L the lift, D the aerodynamic drag and m·F the fuel consumption rate, RE is the Earth radius, and w(h) the known horizontal wind speed (in the flight plane).

To solve the problem, some supplementary models are needed. The Earth Model adopted has the following characteristics:


Earth radius RE = 6356.766 km;

constant gravity g = 9.80665 m/s2;

air, a perfect gas defined by a ratio of specific heats κ = 1.4 and a gas constant Ra = 287.053 J/(kgK);

atmosphere model ISA+ΔΘ, that is, standard atmosphere model corrected for non-standard days by a temperature deviation ΔΘ at sea level, as described in Appendix 2; it defines temperature Θ, pressure p and density ρ, as functions of h.

To simplify the analysis, in accordance with the simplifications already considered, the take-off run is supposed to be formed by only one segment, defined by the following conditions:


all the wheels on the ground;

constant pitch angle (which requires instantaneous rotation at lift off);

take-off engine rating, T = TTO(M, h);

ground effect not considered.

The landing ground run can be formed by various segments, depending on the instants when spoilers, brakes, and reverse thrust are applied. To simplify the analysis, only one segment is considered, defined by the following conditions:


all the wheels on the ground;

constant pitch angle (instantaneous rotation at TD);

brakes and spoilers applied during the whole run;

idle engine rating, T = TIDLE(M, h) (no reverse);

ground effect not considered.

The first course change must be performed when the aircraft reaches a horizontal distance of 5.8 nmi from BRA DVOR/DME (following ATC regulations, this first course change must not be performed before reaching a height AGL of 400 ft). This requirement defines the first waypoint (WPT 1). The procedure defines two more waypoints:


RBO (WPT 2);

PINAR (WPT 3).

This procedure defines the following waypoints:


ROLIS (it is the last route waypoint);

ETARU (WPT 40);

FFM (Frankfurt Main, WPT 41);

MTR (IAF, WPT 42).

The following flight intent defines the flight procedure to be followed. It is not a complete description of the vertical profile, in the sense that, in general, many trajectories may comply with it; the actual flight segments to be flown are defined in the section ‘Flight segments’


initial climb at γ = 3°;

MCLB rating at hAGL = 1500 ft;

acceleration at hAGL = 3000 ft;

climb at CAS = 250 kt;

acceleration at hp = 10,000 ft;

climb CAS/Mach 290 kt/0.78;

cruise at hp = 33,000 ft and M = 0.80;

descent with IDLE rating;

descent Mach/CAS 0.78/290 kt;

deceleration at hp = 10,000 ft;

descent at CAS = 250 kt;

deceleration at hAGL = 4000 ft;

final descent at γg = −3°.

In the definition of this flight, the following operational speeds (CAS) are considered, for the nominal WTO (obtained from BADA15):


lift off, VLOF = 146.4 kt;

initial climb, V2 + 15 = 161.4 kt;

approach, Vapp = 125.7 kt (obtained during the computation, for the actual weight).
